AMD
AMD is one of the critical customers of Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, representing 7% of its revenue.

EUV Lithography
Extreme ultraviolet lithography (EUV) represents advanced technology used in semiconductor manufacturing, in which Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company maintains technology leadership.

Apple
Apple is a significant customer of Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, accounting for 23% of its revenue.

Taiwan
Taiwan is the location where Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company's manufacturing occurs, contributing to business continuity risks due to cross-strait tensions.

ASML Holdings
ASML Holdings is the exclusive supplier of EUV equipment used by Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company.<SEP>ASML Holdings is a company that maintains monopolistic control over extreme ultraviolet (EUV) lithography systems essential for advanced semiconductor manufacturing.

Qualcomm
Qualcomm contributes 5% of revenue to Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, positioning it as a key customer.<SEP>Qualcomm is a leading provider of mobile processors in the semiconductor industry.<SEP>Qualcomm manufactures specialized processors that meet the requirements for Edge AI deployment.

China
China is the neighboring country to Taiwan, with which there are cross-strait tensions affecting business operations for Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company.<SEP>China is a country affected by export controls that impact NVIDIA Corporation's potential revenue streams.

Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company Limited
Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company Limited is a major semiconductor fabrication company facing geopolitical and operational risks due to its manufacturing concentration in Taiwan and its critical customer relationships.

NVIDIA
NVIDIA is a major customer of Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, contributing 11% to its revenue.<SEP>NVIDIA is a GPU manufacturer that benefits from increased demand patterns due to the artificial intelligence boom.<SEP>NVIDIA dominates the market with an 80% share in AI training chips, showcasing its leadership in the AI infrastructure space.<SEP>NVIDIA is a technology company known for its work in graphics processing units (GPUs) and related technologies.

Arizona Fabrication Facilities
Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company's Arizona fabrication facilities represent a $40 billion investment aimed at diversifying manufacturing geography.

3nm, 4nm, 5nm Nodes
3nm, 4nm, and 5nm nodes refer to advanced semiconductor process technologies that Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company utilizes for production.

Document ID: tsmc_10k_2024
Document ID tsmc_10k_2024 is an identifier for the specific SEC Filing related to Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company.

SEC Filing
The SEC Filing is a formal financial report, specifically the 10-K Annual Report for Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company for the year 2024.

TSMC
TSMC is a semiconductor manufacturer affecting NVIDIA's supply chain for advanced process nodes.<SEP>Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (TSMC) is a leading semiconductor foundry that collaborates closely with major tech companies for advanced manufacturing technologies.<SEP>TSMC is a manufacturing company that impacts NVIDIA Corporation through supply chain constraints due to its manufacturing capacity.<SEP>TSMC, or Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, is a leading semiconductor manufacturing company known for its critical role in the global supply chain.

NVIDIA Corporation
NVIDIA Corporation is a technology company that reported a record Q3 2024 revenue of $18.12 billion, primarily driven by Data Center revenue.<SEP>NVIDIA Corporation is a leading company in AI infrastructure, known for strong growth in data center revenue.

H100 GPU
H100 GPU is a graphics processing unit produced by NVIDIA, critical for AI infrastructure.

Colette Kress
Colette Kress is the CFO of NVIDIA Corporation who noted the impact of export controls on Data Center revenue.

A100 GPU
A100 GPU is another graphics processing unit produced by NVIDIA, essential for AI applications.

Export Controls
Export controls refer to regulations targeting China, impacting NVIDIA's potential Data Center revenue.<SEP>Export controls are regulations impacting approximately 20-25% of NVIDIA Corporation's potential revenue streams.

Gaming Revenue
Gaming revenue refers to the income generated from NVIDIA's gaming segment, which declined to $2.86 billion.

Microsoft Azure
Microsoft Azure is a cloud service provider that has formed new partnerships with NVIDIA.<SEP>Microsoft Azure is a cloud computing service that is a significant contributor to the demand for AI accelerators.

Jensen Huang
Jensen Huang is the CEO of NVIDIA Corporation who highlighted supply constraints affecting GPU production.

AI Infrastructure
AI infrastructure refers to the underlying technology and services required for AI training workloads.

Data Center Revenue
Data Center Revenue refers to the income generated from NVIDIA's data center segment, which reached $14.51 billion.

Amazon AWS
Amazon AWS is a cloud service provider that has partnered with NVIDIA.

Arizona Fab Development
Arizona fab development is an initiative by TSMC to help NVIDIA reduce supply chain risks.

AMD MI300 Series
AMD MI300 Series refers to AMD's competitive offering targeting similar AI workloads as NVIDIA.<SEP>AMD's MI300 series focuses on targeting inference workloads within the AI infrastructure market.

Google Cloud Platform
Google Cloud Platform is a cloud service provider that has established partnerships with NVIDIA.<SEP>Google Cloud Platform provides cloud computing solutions that support the AI infrastructure market.

Intel Gaudi Accelerators
Intel Gaudi Accelerators are competing products from Intel aimed at the same market as NVIDIA's GPUs.

Alibaba
Alibaba's cloud divisions are part of the semiconductor ecosystem impacted by export controls.

Huawei
Huawei is a semiconductor company affected by U.S. export controls targeting China's capabilities, disrupting traditional supply patterns.

Semiconductor Industry Association
The Semiconductor Industry Association is a trade organization that provides insights and reports on the global semiconductor industry.

Samsung
Samsung is a primary customer of ASML Holdings and a major player in the semiconductor market, particularly in memory manufacturing.<SEP>Samsung is a memory manufacturer facing pricing pressures amid cyclical inventory corrections.

Intel
Intel Corporation is a leading semiconductor company that competes in CPU markets and relies on TSMC for leading-edge process technologies.

ByteDance
ByteDance is a technology company influenced by U.S. export policies affecting its semiconductor capabilities.

Advanced Micro Devices
Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) is a competitor of Intel in the CPU markets, both companies rely on TSMC for advanced technologies.

SK Hynix
SK Hynix is a memory manufacturer that, along with Samsung and Micron Technology, experiences cyclical pricing pressures.

SMIC
Semiconductor Manufacturing International Corporation (SMIC) is a Chinese semiconductor company aiming to reduce reliance on foreign technology.

Micron Technology
Micron Technology is a memory manufacturer affected by inventory corrections and pricing pressures in the semiconductor market.

HiSilicon
HiSilicon is a semiconductor design company under Huawei, involved in China's domestic semiconductor development.

GPU Manufacturers
GPU manufacturers benefit from the demand surge driven by advancements in artificial intelligence technology.

EUV Lithography Systems
Extreme ultraviolet lithography systems are crucial for advanced semiconductor manufacturing processes.

China's Semiconductor Development
China's semiconductor development refers to efforts by companies like SMIC, HiSilicon, and Unisoc to achieve technological independence from foreign technology.

CPU Markets
CPU markets refer to the competitive landscape of central processing unit manufacturing, with major players including Intel and AMD.

Unisoc
Unisoc is a Chinese semiconductor company contributing to domestic semiconductor development efforts, striving for technological independence.

AI Infrastructure Market Analysis 2024
AI Infrastructure Market Analysis 2024 is a market research document focusing on the growth and trends in AI infrastructure and related technologies.

Artificial Intelligence Infrastructure Market
The AI infrastructure market refers to the ecosystem of technologies and services facilitating the development and execution of AI applications.

Meta
Meta, formerly known as Facebook, operates an infrastructure division that contributes to AI infrastructure demand.

Intel Gaudi
Intel Gaudi refers to a product line targeting AI inference workloads, competing in the AI semiconductor space.

Amazon Web Services
Amazon Web Services is a prominent cloud service provider driving demand for AI accelerators alongside other major tech companies.

MediaTek
MediaTek produces processors targeted at Edge AI applications, contributing to market growth.

High Bandwidth Memory (HBM)
High Bandwidth Memory from Samsung and SK Hynix is critical for memory bandwidth requirements in AI applications.

Apple's Custom Silicon
Apples custom silicon is designed to support Edge AI deployments, enhancing performance in AI-related tasks.

Google's TPU
Google's TPU (Tensor Processing Unit) is a custom silicon designed to optimize AI workloads and reduce reliance on competitors like NVIDIA.

Regulatory Concerns
Regulatory concerns refer to issues involving AI capability concentration and implications for national security related to semiconductor exports.

Microsoft's Maia Chips
Microsoft's Maia chips are designed to support AI workloads in a custom silicon framework to decrease dependency on NVIDIA.

Amazon's Trainium
Amazon's Trainium is a custom silicon specification aimed to boost machine learning performance in Amazon Web Services.

Test Financial Document
The Test Financial Document is a financial document dated 2024-09-14, containing insights about NVIDIA Corporation's market performance.

Supply Chain Constraints
Supply chain constraints refer to challenges faced by NVIDIA Corporation due to TSMC's manufacturing capacity.

Data Center Revenue Growth
Data center revenue growth is a key performance measure indicating NVIDIA Corporation's success in its AI infrastructure business.

First Batch Document
The first batch document contains information about NVIDIA.

Supply Chain Data
Supply chain data refers to the information concerning the flow of goods and materials in the supply chain, specifically related to TSMC in this context.
